      <h3>Dangerous Wild Life</h3>
      <h1>Scorpion</h1>
      <img src="/scorpionSpain.jpg" alt="Scorpion" class="smaller-image">
      <p>scorpions can be found in certain regions, particularly in dry and rocky habitats. While scorpions are not as common or dangerous as in some other parts of the world, it's still important to be aware of their presence and take precautions to avoid encounters.

      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>To minimize the risk of encounters, individuals can take precautions such as shaking out shoes and clothing, avoiding reaching into crevices without checking, and wearing closed-toe shoes when exploring rocky terrain. In the event of a scorpion sting, cleaning the area, applying cold compresses, 
         and seeking medical attention for severe symptoms are recommended practices. While scorpion encounters are infrequent, awareness and basic precautions can enhance safety when exploring natural environments in Spain.

      </p>
    </div>
    <h1>Jellyfish</h1>
        <img src="/jellyfishSpain.jpg" alt="Jellyfish" class="smaller-image">
      <p> Jellyfish can be found in the coastal waters of Spain, particularly during the warmer months of the year. While most jellyfish species are harmless, there are a few that can deliver painful stings to humans. It's important to be aware of the potential presence of jellyfish when swimming or participating in water activities in Spanish waters.
          

      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>if stung by a jellyfish, it's important to rinse the affected area with vinegar or saltwater to deactivate the stinging cells. Do not rinse with freshwater, as it can actually worsen the sting. Remove any tentacles that may be attached using a pair of tweezers or the edge of a credit card. Applying hot water or a cold pack can help alleviate pain. If the symptoms are severe or an allergic reaction occurs, seek medical attention.
        One must keep an eye out for warning flags, symbols, or notices posted by lifeguards and local authorities, which provide valuable insights into the current jellyfish conditions. These informative indicators empower beachgoers and water enthusiasts to make informed decisions about swimming and water activities. 
      </p>
