   <section id="etiquette" class="section">
        <h3>Etiquette</h3>
        <h1>Siesta Tradition</h1>
      <img src="/receivingChina.jpg" alt="Siesta Tradition" class="smaller-image">
      <p> 
        The siesta tradition in Spain is a cultural practice deeply rooted in the country's history and lifestyle. Traditionally, the siesta involved a midday break, usually taken between 2:00 PM and 5:00 PM, during which businesses, shops, and schools closed for a few hours. This practice allowed people to escape the heat of the day, rest, and recharge before resuming their daily activities. 
      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>While the siesta's prevalence has diminished in urban areas and modern workplaces, it still holds significance in some regions and smaller towns. In these areas, you might notice a slower pace of life during the afternoon hours, with many businesses temporarily closing and locals taking time to relax, enjoy a leisurely meal, or spend time with family and friends. While the siesta is less rigid in contemporary Spain, it remains a cultural reminder of the importance of work-life balance and adapting daily routines to the country's unique climate and traditions.  
      </p>
    </div>
    <h1> Respect for Arts and Culture</h1>
        <img src="/artSpain.jpg" alt="Art" class="smaller-image">
      <p>
        Respect for art and culture is a fundamental aspect of tourist etiquette in Spain, reflecting a deep appreciation for the country's rich history and heritage. When exploring museums, historical sites, and churches, it's crucial to adhere to the rules and guidelines established by these institutions. These regulations are in place to safeguard the invaluable artifacts, artworks, and cultural treasures that contribute to Spain's identity. Avoiding the touching of artifacts unless explicitly permitted is a key principle. 
      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> 
        Many artifacts are delicate and sensitive to oils and contaminants from human skin, which can lead to deterioration over time. By respecting this practice, visitors contribute to the preservation of these treasures for future generations. Additionally, maintaining a quiet and respectful demeanor within these spaces acknowledges their significance and allows others to appreciate their beauty without disruption. By embracing these customs, tourists demonstrate their genuine interest in Spain's cultural legacy and play a role in ensuring its preservation for years to come.
      </p>
